<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-076-080 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 377 393</DOCID><JOURNAL>Windows Watcher  Sept 1991 v1 n11 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT CompuTh!nk Incorporated 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OLE applets foreshadow plug-ins. (Microsoft Corp.'s MicrosoftWindows 3.1 to include six additional mini applications) (objectlinking and embedding) (News Watch) (Brief Article)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.1 (Graphical user interface) (Productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentEnhancementsGraphical User InterfaceObject-Oriented Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft's new OLE-mini-applications moved from the rumor column to the newssection this month.andP;  Vice President Mike Maples announced in late August thatMicrosoft will bring out six additional applets when it ships Windows version3.1 at the end of the year.andP;  In addition, it has modified several existingapplets (Notepad, Cardfile, Paintbrush) to be OLE capable.andM;OLE, Microsoft's new linking and embedding technology, makes modular&quot;plug-in&quot; software possible.andP;  An OLE server can link or embed its data insideany document created by an OLE client.andP;  The receiving document is called thecontainer.andP;  A container doesn't have to know anything about the data.andP;  Forinstance, an OLE word processor doesn't have to know anything about sound touse voice annotations inside a document.andM;Microsoft plans to illustrate the value of this approach with a series of newapplets: Drawing, Sound, Animation, Font Effects, Formulas (for puttingscientific notation inside documents), and Annotation (the electronicequivalent of Post-it brand sticky notes).andM;Many ISVs see OLE applets as a marketing opportunity.andP;  And corporatedevelopers are eyeing this approach as well, since it makes the work theyproduce reuseable.andO;</TEXT></DOC>